# Functional Array Methods

JavaScript arrays have built-in methods that accept a **callback function** and apply it to every element. These methods replace many common loop patterns with one clean, expressive line.

## forEach — run a function on every element

`forEach` iterates over the array and calls the callback for each element. It does not return a new array:

```javascript
const names = ["Rahul", "Priya", "Amit"];
names.forEach((name, index) => {
    console.log(`${index + 1}. ${name}`);
});
```

Use `forEach` when you want to **do something** with each element (print it, send it, save it) but do not need a new array.

## map — transform every element into something new

`map` creates a **new array** by applying a transformation to each element. The original is unchanged:

```javascript
const prices    = [100, 200, 300];
const withGST   = prices.map(p => p * 1.18);
// [118, 236, 354]  — original prices unchanged
```

The callback receives the element and returns the transformed value.

## filter — keep only elements that pass a test

`filter` creates a **new array** containing only the elements for which the callback returns `true`:

```javascript
const scores  = [85, 42, 92, 37, 78];
const passing = scores.filter(s => s >= 60);
// [85, 92, 78]  — only scores >= 60
```

## Chaining Methods

Because `map` and `filter` both return new arrays, you can chain them:

```javascript
const result = scores
    .filter(s => s >= 60)     // keep passing scores
    .map(s => s + " ✓");      // add a tick mark to each
```

## Arrow Functions — the compact callback syntax

```javascript
// These two are equivalent:
prices.map(function(p) { return p * 1.18; });
prices.map(p => p * 1.18);   // arrow function — shorter
```

Arrow functions with a single expression can omit the braces and the `return` keyword — the expression value is returned automatically.

In the code example below, you will see `forEach`, `map`, and `filter` applied to a product catalogue.

codeExample.code:
// Product Catalogue Processor

const products = [
    { name: "Laptop",    price: 45000, inStock: true  },
    { name: "Earbuds",   price:  2000, inStock: true  },
    { name: "Tablet",    price: 25000, inStock: false },
    { name: "Keyboard",  price:  3500, inStock: true  },
    { name: "Monitor",   price: 18000, inStock: false },
];

// forEach — print all products
console.log("=== All Products ===");
products.forEach((p, i) => {
    const status = p.inStock ? "✓" : "✗";
    console.log(`${i + 1}. ${p.name.padEnd(10)} ₹${p.price}  ${status}`);
});

// filter — only in-stock products
const available = products.filter(p => p.inStock);
console.log(`\nIn stock: ${available.length} of ${products.length}`);

// map — apply 10% discount to all prices
const discounted = products.map(p => ({
    ...p,
    price: Math.round(p.price * 0.90),
}));
console.log(`\n=== After 10% Discount ===`);
discounted.forEach(p => console.log(`${p.name}: ₹${p.price}`));

// chain: in-stock products under ₹10,000
const affordable = products
    .filter(p => p.inStock && p.price < 10000)
    .map(p => p.name);
console.log(`\nAffordable in-stock: ${affordable.join(", ")}`);

